author: sfgate.com
title: Washington QB Jake Browning questionable for Stanford game
text:
The status of Washington freshman quarterback Jake Browning is in question for Saturday’s game at No. 10 Stanford after he injured his shoulder late in the Huskies’ loss to Oregon on Saturday night.
Washington head coach Chris Petersen said Browning was day to day Monday, the typical designation Petersen gives for any player who has not suffered a long-term injury.
Browning, a Folsom High alum, appeared to injure his right shoulder on Washington’s next-to-last possession, which ended with a touchdown pass from Browning to Jaydon Mickens to cut the Huskies’ deficit to 26-20 with 3:35 left. Browning was hurt a few plays before the touchdown pass.
“That was probably one time he didn’t need to escape out of the pocket. We had somebody open who he was trying to find, he just couldn’t see him. And so he flushed out of there and got knocked to the turf,” Petersen said. “Maybe down the road, he does find that guy, but he does a great job of finding guys. Things like that are going to happen.”
When Washington got the ball back with 1:11 remaining, K.J. Carta-Samuels (a Bellarmine Prep alum) was at quarterback while Browning was on the sideline. Petersen said after the game that he didn’t believe it was a significant injury but did not elaborate Monday.
Stanford schedule : Stanford’s game at Washington State will have a 7:30 p.m. kickoff Oct. 31 and will air on ESPN.
Also, Stanford announced that it will host Rice on Nov. 26, 2016, a game that originally was to have been Sept. 3, 2016.
The Cardinal’s 2016 season opener instead will be Sept. 2 against visiting Kansas State, which Stanford will face on the road Sept. 4, 2021.
Utes’ tight end out: Utah starting tight end Siale Fakailoatonga is out for the season after being injured in the 34-18 win against Arizona State on Saturday.
The third-ranked Utes (6-0) play at USC on Saturday.
Fakailoatonga started the past five games after Evan Moeai was lost for season in the opener.
Watts-Jackson released : Michigan State defensive back Jalen Watts-Jackson was released from the hospital Monday, a day after he had surgery on a hip he injured while scoring the winning touchdown against Michigan.
Watts-Jackson came up with a fumble on the final play and returned it 38 yards to give the Spartans a 27-23 win Saturday.
